    &gt; behavior I&#39;m seeing is 
    &gt; that if I attempt to catch the specific exception thrown 
    &gt; by a method (e.g. 
    &gt; catch (java.sql.SQLException e), the catch block fails to 
    &gt; catch it and 
    &gt; Junit logs it as an error. If I use catch (Exception e), 
    &gt; the exception is 
    &gt; caught as I would expect. I find that I can call 
    &gt; getClass() on the caught 
    &gt; Exception and that it returns the expected SQLException, 
    &gt; whereas using 
    &gt; instanceof fails.
    &gt; 
    &gt; Examples (behaves the same using other methods throwing 
    &gt; other exception types)
    &gt; methods are from:
    &gt; public class PersistenceTest extends TestCase {...}
    &gt; 
    &gt;    public static void main(String[] args) {
    &gt; 	try {
    &gt;        PersistenceManager.singleton().write(&quot;insert into 
    &gt; noSuchTable 
    &gt; values(&#39;junk&#39;)&quot;);
    &gt; 	  System.out.println(&quot;No exception writing to 
    &gt; non-existent table&quot;);
